      <h1>JEPQ Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Tech-Focused Covered Call Income Generation</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <p>For investors seeking high current income without entirely sacrificing exposure to the technology sector's growth potential, the JPMorgan Nasdaq Equity Premium Income ETF (JEPQ) has quickly become a standout option. Launched as a companion to the highly successful JEPI fund, JEPQ applies a similar actively managed, covered call strategy, but applies it to the tech-heavy Nasdaq-100 index. This approach aims to deliver a significant portion of the returns associated with the Nasdaq-100 with less volatility. In this analysis, we explore the mechanics behind the <strong>jepq dividend</strong>, review its historical performance, and project its future yield trajectory.</p>

      <h2>Current Dividend Yield & Payout Details</h2>
      <p>The <strong>jepq dividend yield</strong> is the primary draw for the fund. By actively managing a portfolio of Nasdaq-100 stocks and utilizing Equity-Linked Notes (ELNs) to sell out-of-the-money call options, JEPQ consistently generates annualized yields in the 9% to 11% range. This is a dramatic premium over a standard QQQ investment, which typically yields under 1%.</p>

      <p>The fund distributes this income monthly. Investors looking to capture the payout must own shares before the <strong>jepq dividend date</strong>, which is the ex-dividend date—typically the first business day of the month. The cash payout usually hits brokerage accounts three to four days later.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key JEPQ Metrics</h3>
        <ul>
